@node Distribution "Distribution"
Contents of file Stock.lha are in PUBLIC DOMAIN.

Don't send me any money: your contribution to the author should be just
an @{"E-Mail" link Contact} to help me for next versions with suggestions, comments, etc.
or just to say "hallo" (or "your english is ugly" or anything else).
I also like postcards!

Stock may not be sold, but may be distributed everywhere as long as only a
VERY SMALL fee is charged to cover the costs of copying and distribution.
Stock may be freely redistributed via BBSs, InterNet/Usenet, and disk
libraries such as Fred Fish's, as long as the archive is not modified.
Disk magazines and services that charge extra for file transfers may not
distribute Stock.

Please, always copy the whole archive Stock.lha with docs, auxiliary files.

In using Stock, you accept the responsibility for any damage or loss of
productivity/money that may occur through or during its use.  The author
is not and cannot be held accountable.
@endnode

@node SuppliedFiles "Supplied Files"

                     CONTENTS OF DISTRIBUTION ARCHIVE

Name             Type   Comment
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Stock            EXE    English strings on gadgets and messages, sorry.
                        Maybe in second version all will be localized.
Stock.types      AUX    Simple text file containing archive type strings.
                        Convert it in your language.
Stock.guide      DOC    Documentation for V 1.4 in AmigaGuide format.
                        English only.
Stock.help.it    DOC    Help pages file in Italian. Place in TH:

Stock.help.en    DOC    Help pages file in English. Place in TH:

Stock.help.fr    DOC    Help pages file in French. Place in TH:

In this version I won't translate hypertext doc file in other languages
as I did for last version. It takes too much time, sorry.
Sources are not included, but I can think about sending them if you ask
me by @{"E-Mail" link Contact}.
@endnode

@node ReqSystem "Required System"
All you need is an AMIGA with Hard Disk and a drive.
Stock should work with ANY version of KICKSTART !!!

Written in C without any assembly optimization (no need) and compiled on
Amiga 2000 with KickStart 1.3-2.0 switchable, 1M chip ram, 4M fast ram,
Fatter Agnus PAL, STANDARD Denise, double drive, hard disk Quantum 85M.
@endnode

@node WhatIsStock "What is Stock?"
Stock is a STOCKING TOOL very useful to transfer files between hard disk
and disks (any format). It has catalog capability too, I mean Stock can
take a global list of contents of your disks, it manages the allocation
of files to disks (and retrieving to hard disk), optimizing with a
Best Fit algorithm.

If you keep a collection of images, musical modules, compressed PD programs
or something else, then you surely advised that a so big amount of files
takes a very large area on your hard disk. Moving those files to disk isn't
so easy as it could seems: it's necessary to apply full sized labels to
every disk in order to take a note (by pencil) about the current list of 
files inside it.
It's very hard to group files to fill up your disks and waste just a few
blocks on any volume.
Furthermore, it could be very useful to have a short comment for every
archived item, easy to access, modify, delete...

Well, Stock automatically solves all of those problems (and many more,
you'll see) and it's very user friendly and easy to use !!!
Stock can also store files larger than the disk's size, just splitting them
in many disks, and retrieve them in a transparent way.
From V1.3 Stock gives you a very powerful Optimizer to always get the best
disk space allocation.
@endnode

@node Installation "Installing Stock"
First, create a work directory for STOCK on your hard disk,
i.e. DH0:StockDIR (give it any name), then assign the logical device TH:
to it, i.e. "Assign TH: DH0:StockDIR".

Next, copy "Stock" (executable) to ANY command directory, that is any
directory included in your search PATH.;

Copy "Stock.types" to TH: work directory;

Finally, rename "Stock.help.XX" as "Stock.help" and copy to TH: work
directory (where "XX" is the extension for your favorite language).

That's all!
@endnode

@node GenUsage "Usage of Stock"
@prev Installation
Versions 1.x and Beta of Stock don't use any kind of menu and
everything is done by gadgets.
Just after starting, Stock shows an area of file selection on the left, 10
gadgets on the right and a comment area on the bottom of the window.

Stock starts showing a list of available archives.
Now you can perform the following operations:
 @{"CREATE" link OpCreate} a new archive.
 @{"SELECT" link OpSelect} one of listed archives.

Once you have selected an archive you can:
 @{"Show Archive" link OpShowArch} contents of selected archive.
 @{"Show Buffer" link OpShowBuff} directory of selected archive.
 @{"Show Disks" link OpShowDisk} that compose selected archive.
 @{"Optimize" link OpOptimize} selected archive.
 @{"DELETE" link OpDelete} selected archive.
 or just sort archive list by name: in this section you cannot sort by
 disk or by size.

To move files from your Hard Disk to Floppy Disks you have to enter
@{"Show Archive" link OpShowArch} section and to retrieve them back from Floppy Disks to
Hard Disk enter @{"Show Buffer" link OpShowBuff} section.

Use @{"Optimize" link OpOptimize}, @{"Show Disks" link OpShowDisk} and @{"DELETE" link OpDelete} to perform managing operations on
selected archive.

In any time, everywhere in the program, press @{"Help" link OpHelp} key on your keyboard
to receive context sensitive help.
@endnode

########################################################################
##                        Sub-Nodes of GenUsage                       ##
########################################################################

@node OpCreate "CREATE a new archive"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpHelp
In order to Store your files to disk you have to CREATE an archive
structure that you perform clicking on CREATE gadget.
This gadget will be present on @{"List Archives" link OpListArch} mode only.

Then Stock will ask you by requester the name of that new archive, max 16
chars: I suggest you to use very short strings.

Just after that you will be asked to select a type of archive by mouse, on
the same entry area used to select archives or files.
That area now shows the list of types found in Stock.types (that MUST be
in TH:) and loaded at program's start up. That file can be easily
modified by ANY bare-text editor (such as Ed), so you can convert it to
your language, add new types, etc.
It could contain up to 100 types of 30 characters each. Extra characters
and extra types will be ignored.
Archive type is NOT an archive description, it is just a wide class of
files the archive belongs to, such as "PD Programs" or "Images".
For a more specific comment to the archive there are 80 characters of note,
in the 2nd line of comment area: write here your notes.
Stock.types strings could be modified at any time, but the type of your
new created archive will not.

Finally, a requester "LINK NEXT DISK, name <first disk>" will appear.
By version 1.3 of Stock you can create an empty archive or give some disk
already containing your archive data as a base to build your disk sequence.
If you have some of these disks RENAME them with <archive name> +
<sequence number>. i.e.: if your archive name is "foo" your first disk must
be named "foo00", second disk "foo01" and so on, using decimal numbers
up to 99.
Then insert first disk in any drive, answer YES to the requester and tell
the next requester (string) the device name of drive that contains your
disk (such as "df0:", "pc0", "df1:", or any else).
After that Stock will read the directory and add all the files found inside
to the archive structure.
Continue this procedure with second disk, then third one and so on until
you have no more disks to link: then answer ABORT to the requester!
If you want to simply create an empty archive, just answer ABORT to the
first "LINK NEXT DISK" requester.

At this time Stock has also created a sub-directory in TH: named
TH:<archive name> that I'll refere, now on, as "Buffer Directory" or simply
"Buffer".
You can show contents of Buffer by clicking @{"Show Buffer" link OpShowBuff} gadget.
It should be initially empty.
Fill it with files you want to store on disks.
@endnode

@node OpSelect "SELECTION of an archive"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpCreate
When entry area is showing the list of available archives, just click on
one of them to select it.
Stock will display some information on selected archive, such as number of
stored files, number of disks that compose the archive itself, type and
comment to the archive in the comment area.
You can modify the comment to the currently selected archive just clicking
on second line of comment area.
It is just ONE line of comment and this limitation is quite natural because
this comment will be stored as a filenote to the <archive>.stk
file (in TH:).

In the "Archive" area just under the gadgets, Stock always shows
the currently selected archive.

Another way to select an archive is to specify its name in command line
while starting Stock by CLI (i.e. "Stock images"): it is the only one
parameter Stock will accept in command line.
If the specified archive doesn't exist, Stock will start @{"CREATE" link OpCreate} sequence.
@endnode

@node OpShowArch "Archive Contents List"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpSelect
Once you've selected an archive you can see it by pressing "Show Archive"
gadget.
You can sort that list by name, by size or by disk, you can insert a 4
lines comment for each file, selecting the comment area: it's important
to press ENTER at the end of each line in order to correctly store it in
memory!

You can use the "Retrieve" gadget to copy archived files back from Disks
to Buffer so to have them once again at disposal on hard disk.
Then Stock will require necessary disks in order (from 00 to MAX) where the
selected files are stored in. Unfortunately I didn't yet manage to
eliminate the system requester so you should ALWAYS answer CANCEL to it
to let Stock requester appear.

BEWARE: STORE operation MOVES files from Buffer to Archive, but RETRIEVE
operation just COPIES them from Archive to Buffer, without deleting them
from disk.
To delete files, archives or blank disks use the "DELETE" gadget.

If you prevent Stock from accessing disk while deleting archivied items,
it will always delete files from archive, but the physical copy will
remain as a "ghost" file on your disk. Don't worry, the only effect is
that your disk has lost some allocation capacity that you can recover at
any time deleting the "ghost" file.
@endnode

@node OpShowBuff "BUFFER directory"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpShowArch
There is a single Buffer directory for each archive available.

Buffer directory is just a subdir of TH: that contains files that wait to
be moved to disks or that have been just retrieved from.
So move files that you want to store in that archive from anywhere in
your Hard Disk tree to Buffer before starting Stock or simply using
a parallel CLI or SHELL.

i.e.: I want to create an archive Landscapes. After creation, directory
      TH:Landscapes will be at disposal, so I move files to TH:Landscapes
      and click "Show Buffer" to see them.

While showing the list of files in selection area, select now, by mouse,
just one, a subset or none of them, then press gadget "STORE".
If none of them was selected we will be asked for transferring ALL that
files to archive disks, else just selected files will be transferred.
Then Stock will ask you to format a new disk giving it exactily the
required name (use a parallel CLI or SHELL or just prepare your disks
before starting Stock) and to insert it in a drive.

Then you will be asked to specify which device the program must access
that disk through.
That information is necessary since some device of Amiga doesn't
communicate the change of volume to the system, then it will be better
to access all the volumes by device name (instead of volume names)!!!
It ain't necessary to use normally formatted disks, ANY format will be
accepted, i.e. DF0:, PC0:, DS0:, etc.
If you have at disposal more than one drive I suggest you to use them in
an alternate way, I mean even volumes on even drive, odd volumes on odd
drive, i.e. DF0: for Landscapes00:, DF1: for Landscapes01:, DF0: for
Landscapes02:, DF1: for Landscapes03: and so on...

Archiviation is automatically accomplished using a simple BEST FIT
algorithm that examines each time the WHOLE disk list !!!

Using Stock you also can archive files larger than the available blank disk
space: Stock will automatically splits your too-large files in a few parts
that will be merged back together in RETRIEVE operation. To do this Stock
only looks for EMPTY disks. I suggest NOT to store files larger than 8M.
@endnode

@node OpShowDisk "Disk Sequence"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpShowBuff
In this section you can see a list of disks that compose your current
archive.
Additional information, for each disk, are:
1 - Name of device where that volume MUST be placed to access it.
2 - Number of free blocks. The size of each block isn't fixed, but depends
    on used filesystem.
3 - Number of stored files. This number includes not only entire files, but
    parts of files too, for those files splitted in 2 or more disks.
@endnode

@node OpOptimize "Optimize Section"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpShowDisk
In this section you can optimize an already made archive to better allocate
files and save some space or disk.
It starts examinating current archive: it calculates a performance index,
'Actual Optimization Degree': shows you the ratio between archived data
and actually allocated space (on disks) for current archive.
Then some notes or even suggestion could appear on text area: following
suggestions is recommended.
To get a better allocation you can use 2 methods of optimization that you
can select by 'Select' gadget on the right.

COMPACT Method.
  It is a quick method, but gives low performance.
  It moves files from last disk to the holes of free space and deletes empty 
  disks if possible.
  Beware: Fragmented files WON'T be moved with this method!
  It doesn't require a lot of Hard Disk space.

GLOBAL BEST FIT Method.
  It is a slow method, but gives good performance.
  It applies again the same algorythm of allocation, but this time on the
  whole archive.
  It could be very useful because fragmentation comes when files are stored
  a few at a time: so if 'Best Fit' algorythm can look at the whole list of
  files it will give a good result.
  Beware: This operation could take a lot of time!
  It could need a lot of Hard Disk space.
  *** Use GBF method carefully: it's a very big routine and there are a
      lot of things that could be wrong. I have no time to perform a 
      serious debug (in release 1.4), so <<<BEWARE>>>

Once you have chosen and selected your method, proceed to the operation
by pressing OPTIMIZE gadget.

@endnode

@node OpDelete "Deleting an item"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpOptimize
It is an obvious option for Disk, Contents, Buffer or Archive lists: it
deletes selected items.

Whether you discard a file, it cannot be restored.

Deleting a disk is just possible if it is the last one and it's empty.

Discarding an archive simply deletes the index file and Buffer directory,
but leaves archived files on disks untouched, so it will be easy to UNDO
this operation.
If you delete an archive by error, you should remake it moving files to
Buffer from disks again and calling STORE again: a bad work.
This is the case where new feature of creation of archive by linking disks
comes very useful: just link disks again when required.
@endnode

@node OpHelp "ON LINE Help Feature"
@toc GenUsage
@prev OpDelete
Help feature comes with version 1.2
Wherever you are in the program, you can receive some helpful notes by
pressing 'Help' key on keyboard.
It is context sensitive and shows just a single page for every topic.
After reading press 'Esc' key or click 'Thanks' gadget to exit help.

Each time Help is called, Stock accesses Stock.help in TH: directory.
If you want you can modify it to make it better or comprehensible to you,
translate it in your language or just add or remove some note.
There are a few rules you must follow to modify it.
1 - Always use a bare text editor such as Ed.
2 - Max lenght of lines is 60 characters: extra chars will be ignored.
3 - Max number of lines for each topic is 13: extra lines will be ignored.
4 - Each topic starts with a '@' character followed by title of topic.
    It ends where next topic starts.
5 - DO NOT change the topic order!
@endnode

########################################################################
##                     End of Sub-Nodes of GenUsage                   ##
########################################################################

@node LimeRec "Limits and Recommendations"
Important note: DO NOT SWITCH OFF your computer without having closed
                Stock first!
			If you do, some of your archives may be not updated.

There are limitations that you have to keep in mind, in order to
understand some 'strange' behaviour of Stock:
  Max number of disk for each archive:      100
  Max number of files for each archive:    2000
  Max number of types:                      100
  Max length of type strings:                30
  Max number of lines for each help topic    13
  Max length of help lines:                  60
  Max number of parts while splitting files: 10
  Max length of archive name string:         16
As you can see they are very 'large' limits...
@endnode

@node History "Version & History"
This is Version 1.4 of Stock

* Beta Ver:
17 feb 1995: "TOT_DISPLAY + 1" - BUG found by myself.
  It's a minor bug of routine GetSlider proposed by Commodore in Rom
  Kernel Manuals (Ver 1.3). If you click on arrows to shift up or down
  the display list and number of entries is TOT_DISPLAY+1 (13 for Stock:
  TOT_DISPLAY = 12), GetSlider doesn't refresh slider after the first
  click. Static variable 'update' doesn't reset to 0 if number of entries
  is TOT_DISPLAY+1. Sorry, Commodore.
20 feb 1995 -> 25 mar 1995: PARALLEL DEVELOPING OF VERSION 2 FEATURES.
  << You will see all this work on version 2 - MAYBE on september >>

* Ver 1.0:
05 apr 1995: END OF BETA TESTING PERIOD.
  Nobody found any bug (but I'm sure that many people used Stock for some
  time) so I can think it's a reliable program.

* Ver 1.1:
07 apr 1995: "TYPE SELECTOR" - MODIFICATION.
  It was an ugly one the window that I used to select types of archives.
  Now everything works on the same selection area: better look :)
  Max number of types raised to 100: now you can scroll them using arrows
  and slider.
09 apr 1995: "LINK SEQUENCE" - MODIFICATION
  Now you can link a list of disks full of files while creating a new
  archive, or just let it empty as before. Useful if you corrupt or
  delete an index file (.stk) that you need: now you can easily and
  quickly remake your archive.

* Ver 1.2:
13 apr 1995: "HELP ON LINE" - MODIFICATION.
  Let's use that nice button 'Help' on the keyboard to implement a clever
  ON LINE help feature.
  Help files in Italian, French and English. You can change your help file
  as you like, it's easy (see docs).

* Ver 1.3:
18 apr 1995: "OPTIMIZE" - MODIFICATION.
  'Save & Quit' button is the same as the Close gadget. I replace it with
  a new and useful function, OPTIMIZE. Clicking on that new gadget you
  open a new window that gives you a lot of tools to optimize an already
  made archive. Read DOCS about that new function.
21 apr 1995: "COMPACT" - MODIFICATION.
  Adding algorithm to perform "Compact" optimization: low performance, but
  easy and fast method.

* Ver 1.4:
25 may 1995: "STORE deletes files on error condition" - BUG found by Marek.
  If you tell Stock the disk is inserted and system doesn't find it,
  a system requester will pop up. Answering 'Cancel', STORE operation will
  be aborted, but current file will be deleted from buffer.
  Now everything works, I think.
27 may 1995: "Big Archive Names" - BUG found by Marek.
  I've forgotten to limit length of archive names so it overlapped
  requester borders. 
  Now it is limited to 16 chars.
02 jun 1995: "GLOBAL BEST FIT" - MODIFICATION.
  (It's a part of OPTIMIZE modification so version is 1.4 again)
  Adding algorithm to perform "Global Best Fit" optimization: good
  performance, but it could take a lot of time (depending on archive size).
  *** Use GBF method carefully: it's a very big routine and there are a
      lot of things that could be wrong. I have no time to perform a 
      serious debug (in release 1.4), so <<<BEWARE>>>
@endnode

@node ToDo "To Do"
In version 2, Stock will be endowed with configurable menu that allows the
user to accomplish some action directly on archived files with no need to
previously copy them to Buffer Directory.
i.e. It would be nice and smart to be able to view files of an archive of
images from disk, or docs; or extract files from a compressed archive
stored away using Stock.
I'd also like to allow some kind of treatment of files before stocking,
some like compression, coding for error protection, etc.
Furthermore second version will be able to transfer not just files, but
directories also.
I should apply an algorithm to format new disks. But I don't really want
to do it because Amiga is a multitasking system so it's wise to use this
feature: a parallel CLI or SHELL is the best solution. Use a parallel CLI
or SHELL to transfer file from any place of your hard disk to Buffer and
from Buffer to any place.
HELP: How can I avoid system requester to pop up (that one saying "No disk
present in device DF1:") ?
I've placed  -1 in pr_WindowPtr field of current process, but it isn't
enough !
If you can suggest me how to do it, I'll be grateful :-)
Another Optimization method: it will be fast and best performance.
I also want to deplace the Buffer directory from TH: to anywhere you want
in Hard Drive.
@endnode

